Table~\ref{tab:objects} depicts the five object classes defined in \pkg{mixComp}. The first two respectively represent a finite mixture distribution and a random sample drawn from such a distribution. The \code{Mix} object is printed as a matrix of component weights and parameters and is plotted as the density of the specified mixture, showing the overall as well as the component densities. The \code{rMix} object prints as the vector of observations and plots as a histogram, showcasing the individual components as well as the full sample. Both objects contain a number of attributes giving additional information, details of which can be found in the corresponding \proglang{R} help files. 

\newpage
The generation of an object of class \code{Mix} hinges on three central arguments: a string \code{dist} specifying the name of the family of component densities (or kernels) $\{g(x;\theta):\theta \in \Theta \}$, a vector \code{w} giving the weights $w_i$ and a list \code{theta.list}\footnote{The component parameters can also be supplied via the \code{...} argument.} containing the parameters of the component densities $\theta_i, i \in 1, \dots, p$. While the creation of \code{Mix} objects is mostly straightforward, two things should be noted in this regard: First, the \pkg{mixComp} procedures will search for functions called ``r\code{dist}'' and ``d\code{dist}'' in the accessible namespaces. For most ``standard'' distributions, these functions are contained in the \pkg{stats} package and do not need to be user-written (compare with Section~\ref{sec:non-standard}). To make use of these functions, it is essential that the string \code{dist} is named correctly (e.g. to create a gaussian mixture on the basis of the \pkg{stats} package, \code{dist} has to be specified as \code{norm} instead of \code{normal}, \code{gaussian} etc. for the package to find the functions \code{dnorm} and \code{rnorm}). Second, the names of the list elements of \code{theta.list} \footnote{or the names of the \code{...} arguments} have to match the names of the formal arguments of the functions ``d\code{dist}'' and ``r\code{dist}'' exactly (e.g. for a gaussian mixture, the list elements have to be named \code{mean} and \code{sd}, as these are the formal arguments used by \code{rnorm} and \code{dnorm}).

