As a simple example of a given dataset to which mixture models have been applied extensively, take the Old Faithful dataset \citep{R, faithful1, faithful2}. In the context of mixture model estimation, the variable \code{waiting}, which gives the time in minutes between eruptions of the Old Faithful geyser in the Yellowstone National Park, is often considered to be the variable of interest. To estimate the number of components of the mixture distribution that provides a suitable approximation to the \code{waiting} data via \textbf{mixComp}, the raw data vector of observations has to be converted to a \code{datMix} object first. For the sake of exposition we specify all arguments of  the \code{datMix} function, starting with the vector of observations $\textbf{X}$ and the string \code{dist}, specifying $\{g(x;\theta):\theta \in \Theta \}$. As has often been done in the relevant literature, we assume that the data comes from a normal mixture.

% R examples with comments
<<datMix1>>=
obs <- faithful$waiting
norm.dist <- "norm"
@

Second, a named list of length $d$ containing the bounds of $\theta \in \Theta \subseteq \mathbf{R}^d$ has to be created. In this example, $\theta = \{\mu, \sigma\} \in \Theta = \mathbf{R} \times (0, \infty) \subseteq \mathbf{R}^2$.

<<datMix2>>=
norm.bound.list <- vector(mode = "list", length = 2)
names(norm.bound.list) <- c("mean", "sd")
norm.bound.list$mean <- c(-Inf, Inf)
norm.bound.list$sd <- c(0, Inf)
@

Next, the argument \code{MLE.function} contains a single function if $d = 1$ or a list of functions of length $d$ otherwise, specifying the $d$ functions needed to estimate the MLE's of $\theta$ based on $\textbf{X}$ if $p$ were equal to 1 (i.e. the MLE's of the component distribution). If this argument is supplied and the \code{datMix} object is handed over to a complexity estimation procedure relying on optimizing over a likelihood function, the \code{MLE.function} attribute will be used for the single component case. In case the objective function is either not a likelihood or corresponds to a mixture with more than $1$ component, numerical optimization will be used based on \pkg{Rsolnp}'s function \code{solnp} \citep{solnp, Rsolnp}. The initial values (for the parameters of a $j$-component mixture, say) supplied to the solver are then calculated as follows: the data $\textbf{X}$ is clustered into $j$ groups by the function \code{clara} (of the \pkg{cluster} package by \citet{cluster}) and the data corresponding to each group is given to \code{MLE.function}. The size of the groups is taken as initial component weights and the MLE's are taken as initial component parameter estimates. Specifying \code{MLE.function} is optional and if it is not, for example because the MLE solution does not exists in closed form, numerical optimization is used to find the relevant MLE's.


Presuming a normal mixture, one specifies $2$ functions, namely the MLE of the mean \linebreak $\hat{\mu}_{MLE} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i = 1}^n X_i$ and the MLE of the standard deviation $\hat{\sigma}_{MLE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i = 1}^n (X_i - \hat{\mu}_{MLE})^2}$.

<<datMix2>>=

MLE.norm.mean <- function(dat) mean(dat)
MLE.norm.sd <- function(dat){
sqrt((length(dat) - 1) / length(dat)) * sd(dat)
} 

MLE.norm.list <- list("MLE.norm.mean" = MLE.norm.mean,
                      "MLE.norm.sd" = MLE.norm.sd)
@


The last two arguments, \code{Hankel.method} and \code{Hankel.function}, need to be supplied if the mixture complexity is to be estimated based on the Hankel matrix of the moments of the mixing distribution. The reader is referred to Section~\ref{sec:hankel} for further information on how these arguments are to be specified\footnote{In this case, the simplifying assumption of unit variance is made. This would be a poor choice for the \code{waiting} data, so $p$ should not be estimated with one of the methods using these arguments, namely \code{nonparamHankel}, \code{paramHankel} and \code{paramHankel.scaled}, see Table~\ref{tab:inputs}.}. 

<<datMix3>>=
method <- "translation"

mom.std.norm <- function(j){
  ifelse(j %% 2 == 0, prod(seq(1, j - 1, by = 2)), 0)
}
@        
